 accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book offers a fresh look at the status of the scribe in society, his training, practices, and work in the biblical world. What was the scribe’s role in these societies? Were there rival scribal schools? What was their role in daily life? How many scripts and languages did they grasp? Did they master political and religious rhetoric? Did they travel or share foreign traditions, cultures, and beliefs? Were scribes redactors, or simply copyists? What was their influence on the redaction of the Bible? How did they relate to the political and religious powers of their day? Did they possess any authority themselves? These are the questions that were tackled during an international conference held at the University of Strasbourg on June 17–19, 2019. The conference served as the basis for this publication, which includes fifteen articles covering a wide geographical and chronological range, from Late Bronze Age royal scribes to refugees in Masada at the end of the Second Temple period.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 4aAntike. 4aHebräisch. 4aHebräische Bibel. 4aRedaktionsgeschichte. 4aSchreiber.  aScribal profession, Second Temple, Early Bronze Age, Masada, Redaction criticism.1 aDemsky, Aaron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDušek, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEshel, Esther, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEshel, Esther, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLanglois, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLanglois, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLemaire, André, econtributor.4ct